  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the primary danger of AI writing tools is their ability to produce plausible, smooth prose that masks a lack of genuine insight or point of view. The author describes a personal workflow where AI is used as a \"pressure tool\" to generate surfaces, organize ideas, and interrogate drafts, while reserving human judgment for taste, decision-making, and the \"sharp parts\" of writing. Key metaphors include \"clay\" (AI produces raw material for the human to shape) and \"brochure about my actual experience\" (hollow professionalism). The tone is reflective and analytical, aimed at technical writers, educators, and content creators who use AI in production. The core thesis is that replacing oneself with AI is the wrong frame; instead, AI should replace only the mechanical parts of the process, leaving human skepticism and honesty intact.",
